	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>qbradq</b> [ Wed May 04, 2011 11:26 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Drag, using a small capacitor from Vcc to Ground is a commonly used method of "debouncing" the supply voltage for an IC. The few electronics books I have read suggest doing this.
<br />
<br />Keep in mind that a capacitor, especially one of low capacitance, does not create a shunt. I do not exactly understand how it "debounces" the supply voltage, but I know it does not short the circuit.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Drag</b> [ Wed May 04, 2011 12:28 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">qbradq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Drag, using a small capacitor from Vcc to Ground is a commonly used method of "debouncing" the supply voltage for an IC. The few electronics books I have read suggest doing this.<br /><br />Keep in mind that a capacitor, especially one of low capacitance, does not create a shunt. I do not exactly understand how it "debounces" the supply voltage, but I know it does not short the circuit.</div>
<br />"Bouncing" refers to mechanical things, like switches and buttons. As in, when you press a button, it's not a clean transition from open to closed, but the button physically "bounces" against the circuit before it rests. Basically, you see something like:
<br />1-------0101010----------1010101------
<br />instead of:
<br />1---------0------------1--------
<br />for when a button is pressed (1-&gt;0) and released (0-&gt;1).
<br />
<br />The PPU doesn't deal with mechanical things like that when rendering video, and unless I'm misunderstanding the OP, he wants to filter the output of the video, which I think is better accomplished by fiddling with the video-out pin, instead of vcc/gnd. So am I right to be confused here? I see how it would be helpful to add a "debouncing" capacitor between vcc and gnd, but I'm having trouble seeing how it would be conductive to video output.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
